vectorData.altText: 3. The accessory nerve is cranial nerve ______. Enter the correct Roman numeral.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

That's right!  The accessory nerve is CN XI. It controls the trapezius and sternocleidomastoid muscles. Its lesion interferes with shoulder shrug and turning the head to the contralateral (opposite) side.

Five nerves are purely*      voluntary motor. They innervate striated muscle.
Cranial nerves III*, IV, and VI, the oculomotor    , trochlear     and abducens     nerves, control extraocular eye muscles, the voluntary muscles that position the eye in the orbit. The abducens nerve abducts the eye, the trochlear nerve depresses the adducted eye, the oculomotor nerve controls all other eye mvts.
A lesion of any one of these nerves causes the affected eye to be misaligned (strabismus), and eye movements in certain directions to be limited.
Cranial nerve III, the oculomotor nerve*, also carries parasympathetic preganglionic axons that control a smooth muscle in the eye, the sphincter pupillae; parasympathetic input causes pupillary constriction. In a lesion of the oculomotor nerve, the pupil is large (mydriasis)     .
Cranial nerve XI, the accessory nerve, controls the trapezius (shoulder shrug) and sternocleidomastoid (SCM; turning the head) muscles; lesion of this nerve weakens or abolishes these movements.
Cranial nerve XII, the hypoglossal nerve     , moves the tongue; a lesion of the hypoglossal nerve paralyzes the ipsilateral tongue     ; on attempted protrusion of the tongue, the non-paralyzed side dominates, and pushes the tongue toward the weakened side.
again, the function is in the name; it moves the eye within the orbit.
again, the function is in the name; it controls a muscle that abducts the eye within the orbit.
this name is a little more obscure; I won’t explain its just now.
This name describes the ultimate position of this nerve, inferior to (hypo-) the tongue (glossus)

This makes sense! Pupil size is normally determined by a balance between parasympathetic input to the constrictor pupillae muscle and sympathetic input to the dilator pupillae muscle. With a lesion of CN III, in the absence of the parasympathetic input to the pupil, sympathetic input is unopposed, and the pupil is dilated.
The tongue is composed of two paired groups of muscles, each innervated by the ipsilateral hypoglossal nerve. Lesion of one of the hypoglossal nerves paralyzes the ipsilateral group of muscles.
As you’ll see below, with the asterisk, one of these 5 nerves carries parasympathetic (involuntary) outflow as well as voluntary motor output, and so is NOT exclusively voluntary motor.
